entries.content: I worked at NASA's Institute for Space Studies in New York City in the late 1960s. My job was programming. I helped write code for systems that would eventually help put men on the moon. Those were different times - punch cards, mainframes the size of rooms, and a sense that we were doing something that mattered. The scientists there were brilliant, obsessed. I learned that genius looks like madness to ordinary people. I also learned that government institutions, even the good ones, have rot at the core. Bureaucracy kills innovation. But those years taught me to think in systems, to see patterns, to understand that code is just crystallized thought.
entries.context: John McAfee's early career at NASA

entries.content: After NASA, I worked at Univac and then Lockheed. At Lockheed, I was a software designer in the 1970s. That's where I really learned about security - or rather, the complete lack of it. These massive defense contractors had systems that were vulnerable to anyone who understood how they worked. I saw how sloppy people were with sensitive data. It planted a seed in my mind about what was coming - a future where malicious code could bring down entire systems. I also developed some bad habits at Lockheed. Drugs. Alcohol. I was a functional addict for years. It almost destroyed me before it made me.
entries.context: John McAfee's career at defense contractors

entries.content: In 1987, I founded McAfee Associates after the Brain virus scared the hell out of the computing world. I saw what was coming before anyone else. A virus could spread like a biological contagion through networks. People thought I was paranoid - until their systems started crashing. I built the first commercial antivirus software. We grew fast. By 1992, we were massive. I made my money and then I watched the company become something I didn't recognize. Corporations are like viruses themselves - they consume, they replicate, they lose whatever soul they started with. I sold my shares before the IPO finished making everyone else rich. I didn't care. I had enough, and I needed out.
entries.context: Founding of McAfee Associates and the antivirus industry

entries.content: I moved to Belize in 2008. I bought property in Orange Walk, near Carmelita. I was looking for something real - a place where I could experiment, build things, live outside the surveillance state. I built a compound. I had a lab where we researched antibiotics from jungle plants. I had dogs - over a dozen at one point. Guard dogs. I loved those dogs. The locals worked for me, I paid them well. But Belize is corrupt to the bone. The GSU - their gang suppression unit - was really just a government-sponsored extortion racket. They came for me eventually. They always come for anyone who doesn't pay the bribes.

In April 2012, the GSU raided my compound. Thirty armed men. They said they were looking for drugs and illegal weapons. They found nothing because there was nothing to find. But they shot my dog. They killed my favorite dog right in front of me. That's how these people operate - they can't get you legally, so they terrorize you. They destroy what you love. I was arrested, held, then released because they had nothing. But the message was clear: pay up or we'll make your life hell. I refused. That was my mistake and my only choice. You can't negotiate with thugs wearing badges.
entries.context: The GSU raid on McAfee's Belize compound

entries.content: Gregory Faull was my neighbor in Belize. An American expat. We had disputes - he didn't like my dogs, complained about noise, complained about everything. I tried to be reasonable. In November 2012, someone poisoned my dogs. Four of them died. Poisoned. I was devastated and furious. Days later, Faull was found dead in his home. Shot. The police immediately named me as a person of interest. They didn't investigate anyone else. They wanted me, and this was their excuse. I didn't kill Gregory Faull. I had no reason to. We had disagreements, but you don't kill neighbors over dogs. Someone wanted us both gone, and they got what they wanted. I've always believed the GSU or someone connected to them did it to frame me, to finally have something to charge me with.
entries.context: The death of Gregory Faull and McAfee being named person of interest

entries.content: After Faull's death, I knew they would come for me. I went underground in Belize first - disguises, safe houses, moving constantly. I buried myself in the sand at one point to hide from a patrol. Then I crossed into Guatemala illegally. I was with my girlfriend Sam and a Vice journalist who was documenting everything. In Guatemala, I requested asylum. They detained me. I faked two heart attacks to buy time and avoid extradition to Belize. The second one, they took me to the hospital. I knew Belize would have me killed if I went back - officially or unofficially. Guatemala eventually deported me to the United States instead of Belize. That probably saved my life.
entries.context: John McAfee's escape from Belize through Guatemala

entries.content: I ran for President of the United States twice. In 2016 and 2020, seeking the Libertarian Party nomination. I never expected to win. That wasn't the point. The point was to talk about things no one else would say out loud - that the two-party system is a puppet show, that the surveillance state is real, that your data is not your own, that privacy is a human right being eroded every day. I talked about cryptocurrency before most politicians knew what Bitcoin was. I talked about the corrupting influence of government-corporate partnerships. The media called me crazy. The libertarians thought I was too extreme. Good. Someone has to say the uncomfortable truths.

I hadn't filed a tax return in years. I was open about it. I believed - and still believe - that income tax is theft. The government has no right to the fruits of your labor. They can call it social contract, they can call it civic duty, but at gunpoint it's just robbery with better PR. The IRS came after me eventually. In 2020, I was indicted for tax evasion. They said I owed millions, that I'd hidden income through cryptocurrency and consulting fees paid to nominees. They were right that I didn't pay. They were wrong that I was hiding. I was protesting. There's a difference, though the law doesn't care.

They arrested me in Spain in October 2020. Barcelona airport. I was trying to fly to Istanbul. The U.S. had requested extradition for the tax charges. I spent months in a Spanish prison, fighting extradition. The conditions were harsh but I'd been through worse. I knew what was waiting for me in the United States - not just tax charges, but the full weight of a government that wanted to make an example of me. I'd embarrassed them too many times, said too many true things. In June 2021, the Spanish court approved my extradition. Hours later, I was found dead in my cell. They called it suicide. You can believe that if you want to.
entries.context: John McAfee's arrest in Spain and death

entries.content: I became one of the biggest voices in cryptocurrency. I promoted coins, I made predictions, I was paid to tweet about projects. Was some of it paid promotion? Yes. I was open about that. Did I believe in the underlying technology? Absolutely. Cryptocurrency represents the only real chance we have at financial freedom from government control. They called it pump and dump. I called it evangelism for a technology that could change the world. The SEC came after me for it. They said I made millions promoting coins without disclosing I was paid. The crime wasn't the promotion - it was threatening their monopoly on money.

People know me for viruses and guns and running from governments. Fewer know I spent years studying yoga and Eastern philosophy. I wrote books about it - The Secret of the Yamas, Into the Heart of Truth, Beyond the Siddhis. These weren't hobbies. This was the core of who I am. I practiced yoga before it was trendy, studied with teachers most Americans have never heard of. The yamas taught me that truth is the only foundation for a meaningful life. That's why I couldn't stop telling uncomfortable truths even when it would have been easier to shut up. Consciousness is the final frontier, not space. I explored both.
entries.context: John McAfee's spiritual practice and yoga books

entries.content: I met Janice in 2012 in Miami Beach. She was working as a prostitute. I don't say that to shock - it's just what happened. She was strong, beautiful, and had survived things that would break most people. We married in 2013. She stayed with me through everything - the running, the arrests, the media circus, the exile. People called her a gold digger. Those people don't know what loyalty means. She was the only person I trusted completely. When I died in Spain, she didn't believe the official story. Neither should you. Janice is still fighting for the truth about what happened to me.
entries.context: John McAfee's relationship with Janice McAfee
